2. Initialize a variable `gcd_result` to store the greatest common divisor (GCD) of the counts, initially set to 0.
3. Iterate through the counts and calculate the GCD of the current `gcd_result` and each count. In Python, `reduce()` is used to perform this operation more easily.
4. Return true if the final `gcd_result` is greater than 1, otherwise return false.

solutionCode.java:
    ```java
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;

class Solution {
    public boolean hasGroupsSizeX(int[] deck) {
        HashMap<Integer, Integer> counts = new HashMap<>();
        for (int card : deck) {
            counts.put(card, counts.getOrDefault(card, 0) + 1);
        }
        int gcd_result = 0;
        for (Map.Entry<Integer, Integer> count : counts.entrySet()) {
            gcd_result = gcd(gcd_result, count.getValue());
        }
        return gcd_result > 1;
    }
    private int gcd(int a, int b) {
        return b == 0 ? a : gcd(b, a % b);
    }
}
```

